		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?post_type=podcast&#038;p=14551#comment-17298</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I watched the entire podcast and it&#039;s amazing how much valuable information there is in it. I was just going through another round of thinking that I needed more to read to encourage myself to continue practicing since I had been stuck for about a month now. And then Todd pulled out the two books (props!), &quot;The Practicing Mind&quot; by Thomas Sterner and &quot;The Practice of Practice&quot; by Jonathan Harnum. I ordered them last night. If they helped Todd and his students, I&#039;m sure these can help me, as well, plus help my Freshman Engineering students coming to college this September. And Scott was just so encouraging about how practicing walking bass lines really helped him learn harmony and the fingerboard. Virtually EVERYTHING Todd and Scott were discussing rang so true to me and was just exactly what I needed to hear. In the past, I have practiced many of the topics they discussed. It was like they were discussing my own unique situation, which is probably more like the Same situation for the vast majority of bass players out there! This was an extremely helpful Podcast for me at just the right time! One  that I hope to re-listen to many times over!

Thanks for a great 81 minutes of encouragement, instruction, and great mind fusion (almost like it was scripted)!]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I watched the entire podcast and it&#8217;s amazing how much valuable information there is in it. I was just going through another round of thinking that I needed more to read to encourage myself to continue practicing since I had been stuck for about a month now. And then Todd pulled out the two books (props!), &#8220;The Practicing Mind&#8221; by Thomas Sterner and &#8220;The Practice of Practice&#8221; by Jonathan Harnum. I ordered them last night. If they helped Todd and his students, I&#8217;m sure these can help me, as well, plus help my Freshman Engineering students coming to college this September. And Scott was just so encouraging about how practicing walking bass lines really helped him learn harmony and the fingerboard. Virtually EVERYTHING Todd and Scott were discussing rang so true to me and was just exactly what I needed to hear. In the past, I have practiced many of the topics they discussed. It was like they were discussing my own unique situation, which is probably more like the Same situation for the vast majority of bass players out there! This was an extremely helpful Podcast for me at just the right time! One  that I hope to re-listen to many times over!</p>
<p>Thanks for a great 81 minutes of encouragement, instruction, and great mind fusion (almost like it was scripted)!</p>
]]></content:encoded>
